definition.value: A lymph node located in the mediastinum.  Mediastinal lymph nodes are arranged in three groups, one on the lateral, another on the medial, and a third on the anterior aspect of the vessels; the third group is, however, sometimes absent.
An inactive substance, treatment or procedure that is intended to provide baseline measurements for the experimental protocol of a clinical trial.

value.value: An infection affecting monkeys, chimpanzees, and other non human primates caused by a HIV-like virus.

definition.value: A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's physical magnitude.
Size is a morphology quality which describes a material entity's physical magnitude.
A 2-D extent quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's two dimensional extent.
An area is a size quality which describes the two dimensional extent of a material entity.
A physical quality of the thermal energy of a system.
Temperature is a physical quality of the thermal energy of a system.
A dervied mass unit is a derived unit which is a measure of the the amount of matter/energy of a physical object, derived from the base unit for mass.
A 3-D extent quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's amount of 3-dimensional space it occupies.
A volume is a size quality which describes the amount of 3-dimensional space an object occupies.
A femtometer is a length unit which is equal to 1m x 10^-15.
A person who provides expert advice professionally.
The person in charge of the care and superintendence of something, especially a collection.

An individual who conducts scientific research. In a clinical setting this individual actually conducts and/or supervises the clinical investigation and study-related procedures. The investigator monitors the safety of the trial subjects and investigational staff (under whose immediate direction an agent is administered or dispensed to a subject). The investigator collects and analyses data and study documents, and provides reports in compliance with applicable requirements. [ NCI ]
A person who presents or submits something (e.g., a proposal or protocol) for formal consideration or review by others. [ NCI ]
An information entity about the status of a publication describing the experiment.
A cell component comparison study design in which RNA from different cell components is examined.
A design in which RNA from different cell components is examined.

A cell cycle design study design type is one that assays events that occurs in relation to the cell cycle, which is the period between the formation of a cell, by division of its mother cell and the time when the cell itself divides to form two daughter cells.
A cell type study design experiment design type compares cells of different type for example different cell lines.

A development or differentiation study design type assays events associated with development or differentiation or moving through a life cycle. Development applies to organism(s) acquiring a mature state, and differentiation applies to cells acquiring specialized functions.

An imprinting study design type compares differences in genetic imprinting of maternally- and paternally-inherited chromosomes (e.g., due to in vivo differences in chemical modification and/or chromatin structure).
A genotype study design type compares genotype, haplotype, or other individual genetic characteristics.
An innate behaviour study design type in which the innate behavior of the organism is examined, e.g. path finding in bees.
An organism part comparison study design type compares tissues, regions, organs within or between organisms.
A design that compares samples from live and dead organisms.
A sex study design type assays differences associated with an organism's sex, gender or mating type.
A species study design type assays differences between distinct species.
A strain or line study design type assays differences between multiple strains, cultivars, serovars, isolates, lines from organisms of a single species.
A compound treatment study design type is where the response to administration of a compound or chemical (including biological compounds such as hormones) is assayed.

A disease state study design type in which the pathological condition of a part, organ, or system of an organism is studied. The etiology may be from infection, genetic defect, or environmental stress.
A dose response study design type examines the relationship between the size of the administered dose and the extent of the response of the organism(s).
A genetic modification study design type is where an organism(s) has had genetic material removed, rearranged, mutagenized or added, such as knock out.

A growth condition study design type is where some part of the growth condition is changed for the purposes of the experiment, examples of growth conditions changed are media, temperature, humidity, light, nutrients.
An injury study design type is where the response of an organism(s) to injury or damage is studied.
A pathogenicity study design type is where an infective agent such as a bacterium, virus, protozoan, fungus etc. infects a host organism(s) and the infective agent is assayed.
A stimulus or stress study design type is where the response of an organism(s) to the stress or stimulus is studied, e.g. osmotic stress, heat shock, radiation exposure, behavioral treatment etc.
An all pairs study design type is where all labeled extracts are compared to every other labeled extract.
An experiment in which the array platform is compared, e.g. Agilent versus Affy.
A dye swap study design type where the label orientations are reversed. exact synonym: flip dye, dye flip
A hardware variation study design type compares different types of hardware for performance, reproducibility, accuracy and precision.
